50|$|<b>Zillmerisation</b> {{relates to}} the {{valuation}} of a life insurance company by an actuary.|$|E
50|$|Depending on what {{reporting}} basis is being used, new business strain can be eased {{by the use}} of <b>Zillmerisation</b> or a Deferred acquisition cost asset. As a result, local GAAP accounting and IFRS accounting tends to show much lower levels of new business strain than regulatory accounting.|$|E
50|$|When new regular premium {{protection}} business (such as life or critical illness insurance) is written, {{the value}} of the company may reduce (when viewed on a regulatory basis) even if the business is likely to be profitable. This effect is known as new business strain and is due to the requirement for the insurer to hold day 1 capital reserves that are higher than the initial premium payments from customers. <b>Zillmerisation</b> is one method of adjusting a net premium valuation to ease this initial strain.|$|E

